</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The pulmonary veins carry oxygenated blood from the lungs to the heart, but their importance to the radiologist extends far beyond this seemingly straightforward function. The anatomy of the pulmonary veins is variable among patients, with several noteworthy variant and anomalous patterns, including supernumerary pulmonary veins, a common ostium, anomalous pulmonary venous return, and levoatriocardinal veins. Differences in pulmonary vein anatomy and the presence of variant or anomalous anatomy can be of critical importance, especially for preoperative planning of pulmonary and cardiac surgery. The enhancement or lack of enhancement of the pulmonary veins can be a clue to clinically important disease, and the relationship of masses to the pulmonary veins can herald cardiac invasion. The pulmonary veins are also an integral part of thoracic interventions, including lung transplantation, pneumonectomy, and radiofrequency ablation for atrial fibrillation. This fact creates a requirement for radiologists to have knowledge of the pre- and postoperative imaging appearances of the pulmonary veins. Many of these procedures are associated with important potential complications involving the pulmonary veins, for which diagnostic imaging plays a critical role. A thorough knowledge of the pulmonary veins and a proper radiologic approach to their evaluation is critical for the busy radiologist who must incorporate the pulmonary veins into a routine “search pattern” at computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance imaging. This article is a comprehensive CT-based imaging review of the pulmonary veins, including their embryology, anatomy (typical and anomalous), surgical implications, pulmonary vein thrombosis, pulmonary vein stenosis, pulmonary vein pseudostenosis, and the relationship of tumors to the pulmonary veins.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2017</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017170050">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2017170050">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig1.jpeg" height="1229" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Development of the pulmonary vein. <i>1:</i> Drawing of the short-axis view. The primary heart tube is formed by the fusion of the bilateral vitelline veins. The point of fusion is called the ventral mesocardium. The dorsal aspect of the primary heart tube at the dorsal mesocardium is initially open, connecting the heart to the splanchnic mesoderm that overlies the embryonic pharynx. The pulmonary vein develops from the vascular plexus in the splanchnic mesoderm and enters the dorsal heart tube (left atrium) through the dorsal mesocardium. <i>2, 3:</i> Drawings of the lateral view <i>(2)</i> and long-axis view <i>(3)</i> of the heart region of a Carnegie stage 16 embryo. Blood returning from the lung buds initially drains into the splanchnic plexus. The splanchnic venous plexus, which extends from the heart to the liver, communicates with the paired cardinal veins as well as the umbilicovitelline veins. The primitive pulmonary vein is formed within the mediastinal splanchnic mesoderm and connects to the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>, as shown in the drawing in <i>3</i>. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <i>4:</i> Drawing of the lateral view. Later, the pulmonary venous connections to the cardinal and umbilicovitelline veins disappear. Four pulmonary venous tributaries of the primitive pulmonary vein subsequently develop and assimilate into the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. <i>IVC</i> = inferior vena cava, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig2.jpeg" height="1112" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Most common arrangement of the pulmonary veins. Coronal oblique CT angiographic maximum intensity projection image of a 56-year-old man shows the most common arrangement of the pulmonary veins: a right superior pulmonary vein <i>(RSPV)</i>, a right inferior pulmonary vein <i>(RIPV)</i>, a left superior pulmonary vein <i>(LSPV),</i> and a left inferior pulmonary vein <i>(LIPV)</i>. The two right pulmonary veins are usually separated by left atrial tissue (<b>*</b>), and the two left pulmonary veins are not distinctly separated by left atrial tissue (arrowhead). <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>MPa</i> = main pulmonary artery, <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig3a.jpeg" height="1124" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Distinguishing a common pulmonary vein ostium from separate ostia. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LIPV</i> = left inferior pulmonary vein, <i>LSPV</i> = left superior pulmonary vein. Multiple CT angiographic maximum intensity projection multiplanar reformatted images are used for evaluation of the pulmonary vein ostia. Extrapolating the left atrial contour (dashed line) is useful in establishing the expected location of the pulmonary venoatrial junction. <b>(a)</b> If the pulmonary vein walls touch the left atrial contour (arrowheads), then these ostia can be considered as separate ostia, even if there is no left atrial wall intervening between the pulmonary veins, as shown in this 36-year-old woman. <b>(b, c)</b> If the pulmonary vein walls do not contact the left atrial wall line (arrowheads), then a common ostium is present. The common ostium (<b>*</b>) can be short <b>(b)</b>, as shown in this 55-year-old man, or can be long <b>(c)</b>, as shown in this 51-year-old man.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig3b.jpeg" height="1196" width="1761" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Distinguishing a common pulmonary vein ostium from separate ostia. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LIPV</i> = left inferior pulmonary vein, <i>LSPV</i> = left superior pulmonary vein. Multiple CT angiographic maximum intensity projection multiplanar reformatted images are used for evaluation of the pulmonary vein ostia. Extrapolating the left atrial contour (dashed line) is useful in establishing the expected location of the pulmonary venoatrial junction. <b>(a)</b> If the pulmonary vein walls touch the left atrial contour (arrowheads), then these ostia can be considered as separate ostia, even if there is no left atrial wall intervening between the pulmonary veins, as shown in this 36-year-old woman. <b>(b, c)</b> If the pulmonary vein walls do not contact the left atrial wall line (arrowheads), then a common ostium is present. The common ostium (<b>*</b>) can be short <b>(b)</b>, as shown in this 55-year-old man, or can be long <b>(c)</b>, as shown in this 51-year-old man.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig3c.jpeg" height="1196" width="1788" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Distinguishing a common pulmonary vein ostium from separate ostia. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LIPV</i> = left inferior pulmonary vein, <i>LSPV</i> = left superior pulmonary vein. Multiple CT angiographic maximum intensity projection multiplanar reformatted images are used for evaluation of the pulmonary vein ostia. Extrapolating the left atrial contour (dashed line) is useful in establishing the expected location of the pulmonary venoatrial junction. <b>(a)</b> If the pulmonary vein walls touch the left atrial contour (arrowheads), then these ostia can be considered as separate ostia, even if there is no left atrial wall intervening between the pulmonary veins, as shown in this 36-year-old woman. <b>(b, c)</b> If the pulmonary vein walls do not contact the left atrial wall line (arrowheads), then a common ostium is present. The common ostium (<b>*</b>) can be short <b>(b)</b>, as shown in this 55-year-old man, or can be long <b>(c)</b>, as shown in this 51-year-old man.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig4.jpeg" height="1875" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Common variations in pulmonary venous drainage. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. Pairings of a contrast material–enhanced CT angiographic multiplanar reformatted image (left) with the corresponding representative schematic drawing (right) from five different patients show the most common pulmonary vein branching patterns on the right and the left. Top left: <i>R2a:</i> Images from a 63-year-old woman show the R2a pattern, which is the most common pattern on the right, with two atrial ostia for the right superior pulmonary vein <i>(RSPV)</i> and the right inferior pulmonary vein <i>(RIPV)</i>, respectively. The right middle lobe vein <i>(RML)</i> joins with the right upper lobe vein <i>(RUL)</i> less than 1 cm from the ostium. Middle left: <i>R3a:</i> Images from a 58-year-old woman show the R3a pattern, which is the second most common pattern on the right, with three atrial ostia. R3a differs from R2a because there is a separate ostium (arrow) for the right middle lobe vein <i>(RML)</i>. <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein, <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein, <i>RUL</i> = right upper lobe vein. Bottom left: <i>R2b:</i> Images from a 32-year-old man show the R2b pattern, which is the third most common pattern on the right and is similar to the R2a pattern, except that the right middle lobe vein <i>(RML)</i> joins with the right upper lobe vein <i>(RUL)</i> at a distance of 1 cm or more from the right superior pulmonary vein <i>(RSPV)</i> ostium. <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein. Top right: <i>L2b:</i> Images from a 40-year-old woman show the L2b pattern, which is the most common pattern on the left, with two atrial ostia for the left superior pulmonary vein <i>(LSPV)</i> and the left inferior pulmonary vein <i>(LIPV)</i>, respectively; however, these two ostia are not separated by atrial wall (orange arrows). Middle right: <i>L2a:</i> Images from a 41-year-old woman show the L2a pattern, which is the second most common pattern on the left, with two separate ostia for the left superior pulmonary vein <i>(LSPV)</i> and the left inferior pulmonary vein <i>(LIPV)</i>, respectively; however, the two ostia are separated by distinct left atrial tissue (pink arrows). (The classification scheme for pulmonary venous drainage patterns is from reference <a href="#r5" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r5">5</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig5.jpeg" height="1671" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Right top pulmonary vein in a 39-year-old man. CT angiographic multiplanar reformatted image shows a right top pulmonary vein <i>(R TOP PV)</i>, a supernumerary pulmonary vein that drains the apical right upper lobe and inserts medial and superior to the right superior pulmonary vein <i>(RSPV)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig6a.jpeg" height="1671" width="1735" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Bilateral supernumerary pulmonary veins in a 71-year-old man. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection image <b>(a)</b>, three-dimensional volume-rendered multiplanar reformatted image (inset on <b>a</b>), and axial CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> show a rare case with both a right top pulmonary vein (green arrows) and a left top pulmonary vein (blue arrows) in a single patient. These veins drain the bilateral lung apices into the superior aspect of the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. Note the characteristic course of the right top pulmonary vein, which passes posterior and medial to the right main bronchus on the right.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig6b.jpeg" height="1671" width="1615" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Bilateral supernumerary pulmonary veins in a 71-year-old man. Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection image <b>(a)</b>, three-dimensional volume-rendered multiplanar reformatted image (inset on <b>a</b>), and axial CT angiographic image <b>(b)</b> show a rare case with both a right top pulmonary vein (green arrows) and a left top pulmonary vein (blue arrows) in a single patient. These veins drain the bilateral lung apices into the superior aspect of the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. Note the characteristic course of the right top pulmonary vein, which passes posterior and medial to the right main bronchus on the right.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig7a.jpeg" height="1379" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Right inferior pulmonary vein pericardial recess in two patients. Pericardial recesses encase each pulmonary vein as it crosses the pericardium. These recesses can become filled with fluid, simulating a mass or lymph node. They can be seen superior to the vein, at the level of the vein, or inferior to the vein. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 38-year-old man shows a pericardial recess (arrowheads) located superior to the right inferior pulmonary vein. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 65-year-old man shows a pericardial recess (arrowhead) located inferior to the right inferior pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig7b.jpeg" height="1379" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Right inferior pulmonary vein pericardial recess in two patients. Pericardial recesses encase each pulmonary vein as it crosses the pericardium. These recesses can become filled with fluid, simulating a mass or lymph node. They can be seen superior to the vein, at the level of the vein, or inferior to the vein. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 38-year-old man shows a pericardial recess (arrowheads) located superior to the right inferior pulmonary vein. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 65-year-old man shows a pericardial recess (arrowhead) located inferior to the right inferior pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig8.jpeg" height="1818" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Intrapericardial portion compared with extrapericardial portion of the pulmonary veins in a 64-year-old man. Top: Axial contrast-enhanced CT image; area within blue square is enlarged at bottom. Bottom: Enlarged area of top image shows the two parts of any given pulmonary vein <i>(PV)</i>, the intrapericardial portion (red shading) and the extrapericardial portion (blue shading), which are separated by the pericardium. When there is a paucity of epicardial fat or mediastinal fat, this distinction may not be visible. <b>*</b> = epicardial fat.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig9.jpeg" height="1540" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. <i>Rhizopus microsporus</i> infection invasive of the pericardium by way of the left inferior pulmonary vein in a 51-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows infectious consolidation that encases (<b>*</b>) and obliterates the left inferior pulmonary vein (black arrowhead). This consolidation crosses the pericardial plane (dashed line), a finding that is consistent with involvement of the intrapericardial portion of the pulmonary vein and, thus, with cardiac invasion. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, yellow arrowheads = pericardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig10.jpeg" height="2865" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Examples of cardiac and noncardiac invasion vis-à-vis the pulmonary veins. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <i>Left panel:</i> No cardiac invasion by lung cancer in two different patients. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images of a 55-year-old man (top left) and a 74-year-old man (bottom left) show no cardiac invasion by lung cancer (<b>*</b>). Tumor is separated from the pulmonary veins and pericardium (green arrowhead) by mediastinal fat (yellow arrowheads). <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein, <i>RIPV Os</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein ostium. <i>Right panel:</i> Cardiac invasion in two different patients. Axial contrast-enhanced CT images of a 63-year-old man (top right) and a 61-year-old man (bottom right) show that invasion by lung cancer (white <b>*</b>) is identified when tumor is seen deep (pink <b>*</b>) to the pericardial plane (dashed line), a finding consistent with involvement of the intrapericardial portion of the pulmonary vein. Obliteration of a pulmonary vein (top left) is not a reliable indicator of cardiac invasion. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, green arrowhead = pericardium, <i>LIPV Os</i> = left inferior pulmonary vein ostium, <i>RIPV Os</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein ostium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig11.jpeg" height="1144" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Myocardial sleeves. <i>PV</i> = pulmonary vein. Left: Photomicrograph of a cross-section of a histopathologic specimen through the right superior pulmonary vein shows a left atrial myocardial sleeve, which is contiguous with the left atrial myocardium (<b>*</b>) and envelops the pulmonary vein wall, becoming thinner as it extends away from the venoatrial junction. (Masson trichrome stain; original magnification, ×10). Right: Representative schematic drawing shows the left atrial myocardial sleeve. Myocardial sleeves are thought to contain arrhythmogenic foci related to atrial fibrillation. Ablation techniques are used to attempt to isolate this arrhythmogenic conduction source from the remaining portions of the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig12a.jpeg" height="1664" width="1024" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Normal pulmonary vein arrangement at the pulmonary hilum at frontal chest radiography of a 44-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows the hilar angle. <b>(b)</b> Frontal chest radiograph with superimposed colored vessels from a three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows that the superior pulmonary veins on either side (blue) form the superior margin of the hilar angle (dotted line). The inferior margin of the hilar angle is formed by the interlobar pulmonary artery <i>(IPA;</i> red). The hilar angle is an important marker of a normal hilum, with a normal hilar angle usually measuring greater than 90°. <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig12b.jpeg" height="1664" width="1024" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Normal pulmonary vein arrangement at the pulmonary hilum at frontal chest radiography of a 44-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows the hilar angle. <b>(b)</b> Frontal chest radiograph with superimposed colored vessels from a three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image shows that the superior pulmonary veins on either side (blue) form the superior margin of the hilar angle (dotted line). The inferior margin of the hilar angle is formed by the interlobar pulmonary artery <i>(IPA;</i> red). The hilar angle is an important marker of a normal hilum, with a normal hilar angle usually measuring greater than 90°. <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig13.jpeg" height="1050" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Asymmetric diminished enhancement of the left inferior pulmonary vein in a 59-year-old man with a left lower lobe pulmonary artery embolism. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric decreased enhancement of the left inferior pulmonary vein (arrowhead) relative to that of the right inferior pulmonary vein in a patient with a left lower lobe pulmonary artery embolism (arrow) and a left lower lobe pulmonary infarction (<b>*</b>). The decreased enhancement is secondary to diminished flow in the vein, which is due to increased pulmonary vascular resistance resulting from the pulmonary embolism and pulmonary infarction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig14a.jpeg" height="1562" width="1939" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Asymmetric enhancement of the right pulmonary veins in a 23-year-old woman with complete thrombosis of a common right pulmonary vein at the ostium after cardiac surgery. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows asymmetric decreased enhancement of the pulmonary arteries on the right (arrowheads), a finding that indicates increased pulmonary vascular resistance on the right side. This finding should prompt a search for pathologic conditions of the pulmonary arteries, lung, and pulmonary veins that would restrict forward blood flow. No pulmonary veins are depicted as opacifying with contrast material in the right lung. In this case, there was complete thrombosis of the right pulmonary veins at their ostia (circle). Note the associated imaging findings of pulmonary hemorrhage and edema (<b>*</b>). Inset: Coronal multiplanar reformatted image shows decreased enhancement (arrowhead) of the right pulmonary artery <i>(RPa)</i>, compared with that of the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPa)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a hyperattenuating clot in the common right pulmonary vein (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig14b.jpeg" height="1562" width="1810" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Asymmetric enhancement of the right pulmonary veins in a 23-year-old woman with complete thrombosis of a common right pulmonary vein at the ostium after cardiac surgery. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows asymmetric decreased enhancement of the pulmonary arteries on the right (arrowheads), a finding that indicates increased pulmonary vascular resistance on the right side. This finding should prompt a search for pathologic conditions of the pulmonary arteries, lung, and pulmonary veins that would restrict forward blood flow. No pulmonary veins are depicted as opacifying with contrast material in the right lung. In this case, there was complete thrombosis of the right pulmonary veins at their ostia (circle). Note the associated imaging findings of pulmonary hemorrhage and edema (<b>*</b>). Inset: Coronal multiplanar reformatted image shows decreased enhancement (arrowhead) of the right pulmonary artery <i>(RPa)</i>, compared with that of the left pulmonary artery <i>(LPa)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows a hyperattenuating clot in the common right pulmonary vein (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig15.jpeg" height="1566" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Central filling defect in a pulmonary vein secondary to a mixing artifact in a 61-year-old man. Axial CT angiographic image shows a central filling defect in a pulmonary vein (arrow), a finding resembling a pulmonary embolism. Filling defects in pulmonary veins on pulmonary CT angiograms are usually due to a mixture of contrast-enhanced and nonenhanced blood in the pulmonary veins. Inset: Axial CT angiographic image shows that in this case, inconsistent opacification of the left atrium and pulmonary vein ostia is depicted. Diagnosis of a thrombus or embolism in a pulmonary vein should be made only when there is homogeneous opacification of the left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig16.jpeg" height="1516" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Creation of a pulmonary vein cuff during lung transplantation. <i>LIPV</i> = left inferior pulmonary vein, <i>LSPV</i> = left superior pulmonary vein. Left: Drawing of the donor’s organs shows that during lung transplantation, a cuff of left atrial tissue <i>(LA Cuff)</i> from the donor patient is excised, which incorporates all of the ipsilateral pulmonary veins draining the donor lung. Right: Drawing of the recipient’s organs shows that this cuff of left atrial tissue <i>(Donor LA Cuff)</i> is then sutured to the recipient patient’s left atrium, creating a continuous venous connection between the donor lung and the recipient’s heart and maintaining the donor lung’s pulmonary vein arrangement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig17a.jpeg" height="1330" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Normal CT appearance of the pulmonary veins after lung transplantation in three different patients. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LA Cuff</i> = left atrial cuff. <b>(a, b)</b> CT images of a 33-year-old woman <b>(a)</b> and a 26-year-old woman <b>(b)</b> show that the left atrial cuff may be depicted as an area of indentation or as a caliber change (arrows on <b>a, b</b>). <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein, <i>RMPV</i> = right middle pulmonary vein, <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein. <b>(c)</b> CT image of a 34-year-old man shows that the left atrial cuff may be depicted as a change in wall thickness (orange arrow) or as an area with adjacent surgical clips (blue arrow) near the pulmonary veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig17b.jpeg" height="1330" width="1485" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Normal CT appearance of the pulmonary veins after lung transplantation in three different patients. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LA Cuff</i> = left atrial cuff. <b>(a, b)</b> CT images of a 33-year-old woman <b>(a)</b> and a 26-year-old woman <b>(b)</b> show that the left atrial cuff may be depicted as an area of indentation or as a caliber change (arrows on <b>a, b</b>). <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein, <i>RMPV</i> = right middle pulmonary vein, <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein. <b>(c)</b> CT image of a 34-year-old man shows that the left atrial cuff may be depicted as a change in wall thickness (orange arrow) or as an area with adjacent surgical clips (blue arrow) near the pulmonary veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig17c.jpeg" height="1330" width="883" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Normal CT appearance of the pulmonary veins after lung transplantation in three different patients. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LA Cuff</i> = left atrial cuff. <b>(a, b)</b> CT images of a 33-year-old woman <b>(a)</b> and a 26-year-old woman <b>(b)</b> show that the left atrial cuff may be depicted as an area of indentation or as a caliber change (arrows on <b>a, b</b>). <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein, <i>RMPV</i> = right middle pulmonary vein, <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein. <b>(c)</b> CT image of a 34-year-old man shows that the left atrial cuff may be depicted as a change in wall thickness (orange arrow) or as an area with adjacent surgical clips (blue arrow) near the pulmonary veins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig18.jpeg" height="1419" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Normal CT appearance of the pulmonary veins after lung transplantation with left atrial cuff reconstruction in a 53-year-old man. Axial CT image and three-dimensional volume-rendered CT image (inset) show that in cases of transplantation of a lung with a single pulmonary vein, the single left pulmonary vein <i>(SLPV;</i> green arrow) will typically appear much larger than the native pulmonary veins (yellow arrows). <i>RIPV</i> = right inferior pulmonary vein, <i>RSPV</i> = right superior pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig19a.jpeg" height="1447" width="1343" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Normal CT appearance of the pulmonary vein stump after lobectomy in two different patients. A well-defined pulmonary vein stump of variable length (blue arrowheads) is depicted after lobectomy, with surgical clips (green arrowhead) adjacent to the stump. The stump should completely opacify with contrast material in the absence of a thrombus. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the findings after lobectomy of the left lower lobe in a 57-year-old woman. <b>(b)</b> CT image shows the findings after lobectomy of the right upper lobe in a 40-year-old man.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig19b.jpeg" height="1447" width="1301" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Normal CT appearance of the pulmonary vein stump after lobectomy in two different patients. A well-defined pulmonary vein stump of variable length (blue arrowheads) is depicted after lobectomy, with surgical clips (green arrowhead) adjacent to the stump. The stump should completely opacify with contrast material in the absence of a thrombus. <i>LA</i> = left atrium. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image shows the findings after lobectomy of the left lower lobe in a 57-year-old woman. <b>(b)</b> CT image shows the findings after lobectomy of the right upper lobe in a 40-year-old man.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig20.jpeg" height="1446" width="1057" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Thrombosis of the left inferior pulmonary vein stump after lobectomy in a 44-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows that a well-defined rounded filling defect (pink arrowhead) is depicted at the left inferior pulmonary vein stump (orange arrowhead), a finding consistent with thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig21.jpeg" height="1192" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Schematic drawing shows the theory of pulmonary vein thrombogenesis after lobectomy. A pulmonary vein stump <i>(PV Stump)</i> of variable length is present after lobectomy. This stump has areas of slow flow, especially at the corners (blue circular arrows), and these areas are predisposed to thrombogenesis. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, red arrows = blood flow.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig22a.jpeg" height="1292" width="1197" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Right upper lobe <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> with a sinus venosus type of atrial septal defect in a 29-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> with the right upper lobe pulmonary veins (arrowheads) draining directly into the superior vena cava <i>(SVC)</i>, which is the most common pattern of <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> on the right. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows that the patient has an associated sinus venosus atrial septal defect (double-headed arrow), with connection of the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. This patient with a long-standing shunt also has typical findings of dilatation and thickening (arrowheads) of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig22b.jpeg" height="1292" width="1453" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Right upper lobe <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> with a sinus venosus type of atrial septal defect in a 29-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> with the right upper lobe pulmonary veins (arrowheads) draining directly into the superior vena cava <i>(SVC)</i>, which is the most common pattern of <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> on the right. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows that the patient has an associated sinus venosus atrial septal defect (double-headed arrow), with connection of the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. This patient with a long-standing shunt also has typical findings of dilatation and thickening (arrowheads) of the right ventricle <i>(RV)</i>. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig23.jpeg" height="2071" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Left <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> in a 30-year-old man. Three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic image and a coronal CT angiographic image (inset) show a left superior pulmonary vein <i>(LSPV;</i> arrow) draining anomalously to the left brachiocephalic vein <i>(BCV)</i> by way of a vertical vein <i>(VV)</i>. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>MPa</i> = main pulmonary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig24a.jpeg" height="1833" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Left <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> in a 33-year-old woman. <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic image shows a left superior pulmonary vein <i>(LSPV)</i> draining anomalously to the left brachiocephalic vein <i>(BCV)</i> by way of a levoatriocardinal vein <i>(LACV),</i> with simultaneous normal drainage into the left atrium (yellow arrow). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic image shows the concept of the bidirectional flow (arrows; double-headed arrow) of the left superior pulmonary vein. This type of connection creates a bridge between the left brachiocephalic vein and the left atrium <i>(LA),</i> with a bidirectional shunt and a potential for paradoxical embolism if the flow is reversed (ie, increased pressure in the right side of the heart) from conventional left-to-right flow to right-to-left flow. No intracardiac shunting was seen. This type of connection is different from <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr>, in which no normal connection to the left atrium is maintained by the involved pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig24b.jpeg" height="1833" width="1473" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Left <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr> in a 33-year-old woman. <i>SVC</i> = superior vena cava. <b>(a)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic image shows a left superior pulmonary vein <i>(LSPV)</i> draining anomalously to the left brachiocephalic vein <i>(BCV)</i> by way of a levoatriocardinal vein <i>(LACV),</i> with simultaneous normal drainage into the left atrium (yellow arrow). <i>LV</i> = left ventricle, <i>RV</i> = right ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic image shows the concept of the bidirectional flow (arrows; double-headed arrow) of the left superior pulmonary vein. This type of connection creates a bridge between the left brachiocephalic vein and the left atrium <i>(LA),</i> with a bidirectional shunt and a potential for paradoxical embolism if the flow is reversed (ie, increased pressure in the right side of the heart) from conventional left-to-right flow to right-to-left flow. No intracardiac shunting was seen. This type of connection is different from <abbr title="partial anomalous pulmonary venous return">PAPVR</abbr>, in which no normal connection to the left atrium is maintained by the involved pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig25.jpeg" height="1676" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span>. Scimitar sign in a 32-year-old woman. Radiograph shows the scimitar sign as a dilated and curved tubular opacity (within dashed rectangle) in the right lung, a finding consistent with an anomalous pulmonary vein draining toward the diaphragm. The shape of the vein resembles the Turkish scimitar.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig26.jpeg" height="1724" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span>. Scimitar syndrome in a 40-year-old man. Three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic image and a coronal CT angiographic maximum intensity projection image (inset) show the scimitar syndrome, a constellation of findings including an anomalous “scimitar vein” (blue arrow), which in this case drains into the inferior vena cava <i>(IVC)</i>, ipsilateral pulmonary hypoplasia (arrowhead), ipsilateral pulmonary artery hypoplasia or aplasia, ipsilateral systemic arterial supply (orange arrow), cardiac dextroposition, and an ipsilateral small hemithorax. <i>Ao</i> = aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig27.jpeg" height="2635" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig27" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27</span>. Supracardiac type of <abbr title="total anomalous pulmonary venous return">TAPVR</abbr> in a 56-year-old man with pulmonary hypertension. CT images (top row) and three-dimensional volume-rendered color-coded CT angiographic images (bottom row) show no pulmonary vein connection to the left atrium. Instead, all of the pulmonary veins connect to a single chamber and drain into a left vertical vein <i>(VV)</i>. The vertical vein drains into a large right superior vena cava <i>(SVC)</i>. A large atrial septal defect (double-headed arrow) is shown between the right atrium <i>(RA)</i> and the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. The inferior vena cava <i>(IVC)</i> is normal. The right ventricle <i>(RV)</i> is enlarged owing to a large left-to-right shunt, but the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> is normal in size. The patient underwent successful surgery. The atrial septal defect was closed, and the vertical vein was connected to the left atrial appendage <i>(LAA)</i>. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>PA</i> = pulmonary artery, <i>RPV</i> = right pulmonary vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig27">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig28a.jpeg" height="1589" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig28a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span>. Snowman sign at chest radiography of a 24-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Anteroposterior chest radiographs show that in a patient with supracardiac <abbr title="total anomalous pulmonary venous return">TAPVR</abbr>, the mediastinum has the shape of a snowman at chest radiography. The head of the snowman is formed by dilated mediastinal veins, which anomalously drain the lungs. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered CT image superimposed on the anteroposterior chest radiograph shows a convergence of the bilateral pulmonary veins into a common vertical vein <i>(VV),</i> which forms the left border of the snowman’s head. This vertical vein then drains into a dilated left brachiocephalic vein <i>(LBCV),</i> which forms the superior border of the snowman’s head. The dilated superior vena cava <i>(SVC)</i> ultimately collects all of the venous drainage of the lungs and forms the right border of the snowman’s head. The body of the snowman is formed by the cardiac silhouette, with an enlarged right atrium <i>(RA)</i> on the right and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig28b.jpeg" height="1566" width="1676" aria-labelledby="fig28b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span>. Snowman sign at chest radiography of a 24-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Anteroposterior chest radiographs show that in a patient with supracardiac <abbr title="total anomalous pulmonary venous return">TAPVR</abbr>, the mediastinum has the shape of a snowman at chest radiography. The head of the snowman is formed by dilated mediastinal veins, which anomalously drain the lungs. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered CT image superimposed on the anteroposterior chest radiograph shows a convergence of the bilateral pulmonary veins into a common vertical vein <i>(VV),</i> which forms the left border of the snowman’s head. This vertical vein then drains into a dilated left brachiocephalic vein <i>(LBCV),</i> which forms the superior border of the snowman’s head. The dilated superior vena cava <i>(SVC)</i> ultimately collects all of the venous drainage of the lungs and forms the right border of the snowman’s head. The body of the snowman is formed by the cardiac silhouette, with an enlarged right atrium <i>(RA)</i> on the right and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig28c.jpeg" height="1566" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig28c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28c</span>. Snowman sign at chest radiography of a 24-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Anteroposterior chest radiographs show that in a patient with supracardiac <abbr title="total anomalous pulmonary venous return">TAPVR</abbr>, the mediastinum has the shape of a snowman at chest radiography. The head of the snowman is formed by dilated mediastinal veins, which anomalously drain the lungs. <b>(c)</b> Volume-rendered CT image superimposed on the anteroposterior chest radiograph shows a convergence of the bilateral pulmonary veins into a common vertical vein <i>(VV),</i> which forms the left border of the snowman’s head. This vertical vein then drains into a dilated left brachiocephalic vein <i>(LBCV),</i> which forms the superior border of the snowman’s head. The dilated superior vena cava <i>(SVC)</i> ultimately collects all of the venous drainage of the lungs and forms the right border of the snowman’s head. The body of the snowman is formed by the cardiac silhouette, with an enlarged right atrium <i>(RA)</i> on the right and the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> on the left.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig28c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig29a.jpeg" height="1440" width="1420" aria-labelledby="fig29a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29a</span>. Focal pulmonary vein stenosis in two different patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of a 39-year-old man with fibrosing mediastinitis shows a focal stenosis (arrowhead) of the right superior pulmonary vein near its ostium, as well as adjacent mediastinal soft-tissue thickening (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 65-year-old man obtained 1 year after radiofrequency ablation for atrial fibrillation shows stenosis (arrowhead) of the left inferior pulmonary vein near its ostium. Note the differential enhancement within the vein proximal and distal to the stenosis, a finding that is due to decreased venous flow through the stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig29a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig29b.jpeg" height="1440" width="1530" aria-labelledby="fig29b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29b</span>. Focal pulmonary vein stenosis in two different patients. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image of a 39-year-old man with fibrosing mediastinitis shows a focal stenosis (arrowhead) of the right superior pulmonary vein near its ostium, as well as adjacent mediastinal soft-tissue thickening (<b>*</b>). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 65-year-old man obtained 1 year after radiofrequency ablation for atrial fibrillation shows stenosis (arrowhead) of the left inferior pulmonary vein near its ostium. Note the differential enhancement within the vein proximal and distal to the stenosis, a finding that is due to decreased venous flow through the stenosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig29b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig30" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig30.jpeg" height="1445" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig30" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 30</span>. Focal pulmonary edema secondary to pulmonary vein stenosis in a 51-year-old woman. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a focal stenosis (arrowhead) of the right inferior pulmonary vein with focal pulmonary interstitial edema (<b>*</b>) secondary to impaired venous return.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig30">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig31a.jpeg" height="1513" width="1148" aria-labelledby="fig31a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31a</span>. Pulmonary vein stenosis after right lung transplantation in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after right lung transplantation shows a focal narrowing (white arrowhead) of a common right pulmonary vein. The caliber of the transplanted common right pulmonary vein is similar to that of the native left pulmonary vein (pink arrowhead), which is unusual. Transplanted single pulmonary veins are typically large. Note the diminished enhancement of the right pulmonary vein (yellow arrowhead) relative to that of the left pulmonary vein. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after angioplasty shows that the degree of narrowing in the transplanted vein improved (arrowhead); however, the pulmonary edema (<b>*</b>) and dyspnea continued to worsen. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after a stent (arrows) was ultimately placed, with subsequent resolution of symptoms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig31a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig31b.jpeg" height="1513" width="1553" aria-labelledby="fig31b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31b</span>. Pulmonary vein stenosis after right lung transplantation in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after right lung transplantation shows a focal narrowing (white arrowhead) of a common right pulmonary vein. The caliber of the transplanted common right pulmonary vein is similar to that of the native left pulmonary vein (pink arrowhead), which is unusual. Transplanted single pulmonary veins are typically large. Note the diminished enhancement of the right pulmonary vein (yellow arrowhead) relative to that of the left pulmonary vein. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after angioplasty shows that the degree of narrowing in the transplanted vein improved (arrowhead); however, the pulmonary edema (<b>*</b>) and dyspnea continued to worsen. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after a stent (arrows) was ultimately placed, with subsequent resolution of symptoms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig31b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig31c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig31c.jpeg" height="1513" width="999" aria-labelledby="fig31c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 31c</span>. Pulmonary vein stenosis after right lung transplantation in a 65-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after right lung transplantation shows a focal narrowing (white arrowhead) of a common right pulmonary vein. The caliber of the transplanted common right pulmonary vein is similar to that of the native left pulmonary vein (pink arrowhead), which is unusual. Transplanted single pulmonary veins are typically large. Note the diminished enhancement of the right pulmonary vein (yellow arrowhead) relative to that of the left pulmonary vein. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after angioplasty shows that the degree of narrowing in the transplanted vein improved (arrowhead); however, the pulmonary edema (<b>*</b>) and dyspnea continued to worsen. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained after a stent (arrows) was ultimately placed, with subsequent resolution of symptoms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig31c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig32" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig32.jpeg" height="1496" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig32" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 32</span>. Pulmonary vein restenosis with in-stent thrombosis in a 59-year-old man. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained 3 years after placement of stents within the right superior pulmonary vein and a right middle pulmonary vein to treat pulmonary vein stenosis shows a filling defect (arrowhead) within the right middle pulmonary vein stent, a finding consistent with in-stent thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig32">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig33a.jpeg" height="1583" width="1373" aria-labelledby="fig33a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33a</span>. Left inferior pulmonary vein pseudostenosis compared with true stenosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of an asymptomatic 71-year-old woman shows pseudostenosis of the left inferior pulmonary vein, with an apparent narrowing (arrowhead) of the vein that is due to mass effect (arrows) from the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 35-year-old man with mediastinal fibrosis shows stenosis of the left inferior pulmonary vein, with narrowing (arrowhead) of the vein but no obvious mass effect (<b>*</b>) by adjacent structures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig33a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig33b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig33b.jpeg" height="1583" width="1277" aria-labelledby="fig33b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 33b</span>. Left inferior pulmonary vein pseudostenosis compared with true stenosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of an asymptomatic 71-year-old woman shows pseudostenosis of the left inferior pulmonary vein, with an apparent narrowing (arrowhead) of the vein that is due to mass effect (arrows) from the aorta <i>(Ao)</i> and the left atrium <i>(LA)</i>. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 35-year-old man with mediastinal fibrosis shows stenosis of the left inferior pulmonary vein, with narrowing (arrowhead) of the vein but no obvious mass effect (<b>*</b>) by adjacent structures.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig33b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig34a.jpeg" height="1397" width="1625" aria-labelledby="fig34a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34a</span>. Pulmonary vein involvement with malignancy in four different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 43-year-old woman shows a right upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the right superior pulmonary vein, with nodular expansion (arrowheads) and heterogeneous enhancement of the pulmonary vein walls and lumen, which are contiguous with the mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image and fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose positron emission tomographic (PET) image (inset) of a 59-year-old man show a left upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the left superior pulmonary vein and extending into the left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 28-year-old man shows occlusion of the right superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead) by a large mediastinal thymolipoma (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 46-year-old man with metastatic esophageal cancer (<b>*</b>) shows a heterogeneously enhancing tumor thrombus within the left inferior pulmonary vein (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig34a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig34b.jpeg" height="1397" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig34b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34b</span>. Pulmonary vein involvement with malignancy in four different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 43-year-old woman shows a right upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the right superior pulmonary vein, with nodular expansion (arrowheads) and heterogeneous enhancement of the pulmonary vein walls and lumen, which are contiguous with the mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image and fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose positron emission tomographic (PET) image (inset) of a 59-year-old man show a left upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the left superior pulmonary vein and extending into the left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 28-year-old man shows occlusion of the right superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead) by a large mediastinal thymolipoma (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 46-year-old man with metastatic esophageal cancer (<b>*</b>) shows a heterogeneously enhancing tumor thrombus within the left inferior pulmonary vein (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig34b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig34c.jpeg" height="1266" width="1473" aria-labelledby="fig34c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34c</span>. Pulmonary vein involvement with malignancy in four different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 43-year-old woman shows a right upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the right superior pulmonary vein, with nodular expansion (arrowheads) and heterogeneous enhancement of the pulmonary vein walls and lumen, which are contiguous with the mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image and fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose positron emission tomographic (PET) image (inset) of a 59-year-old man show a left upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the left superior pulmonary vein and extending into the left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 28-year-old man shows occlusion of the right superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead) by a large mediastinal thymolipoma (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 46-year-old man with metastatic esophageal cancer (<b>*</b>) shows a heterogeneously enhancing tumor thrombus within the left inferior pulmonary vein (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig34c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig34d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2017170050/asset/images/large/rg.2017170050.fig34d.jpeg" height="1266" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig34d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 34d</span>. Pulmonary vein involvement with malignancy in four different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 43-year-old woman shows a right upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the right superior pulmonary vein, with nodular expansion (arrowheads) and heterogeneous enhancement of the pulmonary vein walls and lumen, which are contiguous with the mass. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image and fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose positron emission tomographic (PET) image (inset) of a 59-year-old man show a left upper lobe lung cancer (<b>*</b>) directly invading the left superior pulmonary vein and extending into the left atrium. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 28-year-old man shows occlusion of the right superior pulmonary vein (arrowhead) by a large mediastinal thymolipoma (<b>*</b>). <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of a 46-year-old man with metastatic esophageal cancer (<b>*</b>) shows a heterogeneously enhancing tumor thrombus within the left inferior pulmonary vein (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2017170050&amp;id=fig34d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">van den Berg G, Moorman AF. Development of the pulmonary vein and the systemic venous sinus: an interactive 3D overview. <em>PLoS One</em> 2011;6(7):e22055. <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0022055">http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0022055</a>. Published July 11, 2011.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0022055">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21779373/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Development+of+the+pulmonary+vein+and+the+systemic+venous+sinus%3A+an+i